{
  "local_port": 52952,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I format my memory card using cmd?",
  "response": "Formatting a memory card using the Command Prompt (cmd) on Windows can be done using the `diskpart` tool and the `format` command. Here are the steps to format your memory card using Command Prompt:\n\n**WARNING:** Formatting will erase all data on the drive. Ensure you have backed up any necessary data before proceeding.\n\n1. **Open Command Prompt:**\n   - Press `Windows + R` to open the Run dialog.\n   - Type `cmd` or `powershell`, and press Enter.\n\n2. **Run Diskpart:**\n   - In the Command Prompt window, type `diskpart` and press Enter.\n   - You might receive a User Account Control (UAC) prompt asking for permission. Click `Yes` to proceed.\n\n3. **List connected disks:**\n   - In the Diskpart command prompt, type `list disk` and press Enter.\n   - This command displays a list of all connected disks, including your memory card.\n\n4. **Select the memory card:**\n   - Identify your memory card by its size or number in the list. It will usually be smaller than your main hard drives.\n   - Type `select disk #`, replacing `#` with the disk number of your memory card, and press Enter. For example, `select disk 1`.\n\n5. **List partitions (optional):**\n   - You can list the partitions on the selected disk by typing `list partition` and pressing Enter.\n\n6. **Clean the disk (optional, if you want to remove all partitions):**\n   - If you want to remove all partitions and clean the disk, type `clean` and press Enter. **WARNING:** This will remove all partitions and data on the disk.\n\n7. **Create a new partition (if you cleaned the disk):**\n   - Type `create partition primary` and press Enter.\n\n8. **Format the memory card:**\n   - Type `format fs=ntfs quick` and press Enter.\n   - If you want to use a different file system, replace `ntfs` with `fat32` or `exfat`. For example, `format fs=fat32 quick`.\n\n9. **Assign a drive letter:**\n   - Type `assign letter=G`, replacing `G` with the desired drive letter, and press Enter.\n\n10. **Exit Diskpart:**\n    - Type `exit` and press Enter to leave Diskpart.\n    - Close the Command Prompt window.\n\nYour memory card should now be formatted and ready for use.\n\n**Notes:**\n- Make sure you are selecting the correct disk number to avoid formatting the wrong drive.\n- If your memory card already has partitions you want to keep, skipping the `clean` step might be preferable. Instead, you can directly format the existing partitions.\n- The `quick` parameter speeds up the formatting process but does not check for bad sectors. Omit `quick` for a thorough format, which may take longer.\n\nAlways double-check each step to prevent accidental data loss on other drives.",
